https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-64102176probably no big effect until january

Flights were at 65% of prepandemic levels on December 12: https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-12-13/china-air-travel-demand-surges-as-covid-zero-rules-dismantledBut have now crashed to 42% of prepandemic levels: https://www.yahoo.com/now/china-soaring-covid-cases-push-005712980.htmlUnfortunately the Chinese site seems to be down so I can't see what December 2019 levels were, but I'm guessing we'll be around 50-55% of 2019 levels for the month. Probably somewhere around 45-50mn but I don't know without seeing better data
Sept = 44m, but 44% down on last year so normal was about 80m.

Have to revise down given the lockdowns. Less because lockdown (because there are signs of easing) than because the illness is out and the economy is struggling so less people have places to go or money to pay for it
48 million
Aug and Sept data now reported, clearly reporting was held off deliberately before the Party Conference just like with the GDP figures!
Wish we had more recent data, nothing since July :/Is there an alternative source out there with more recent data?

Haven't run numbers, @MrLittleTexas, since my enthusiasm for that dwindled rapidly after I retired, but (a) I expect China to be hit by some degree of everybody else's inflation and near-recession, and (b) I'm guessing that Xi will keep the screws on to prevent The Dreaded Virus and its various Friends-and-Relations from taking over the workers' paradise, and if he doesn't do that an epidemic will be raging. Together, I am guessing (and "guessing" is the operative word) that these factors will inhibit all sorts of travel, especially the relatively expensive kind. Throw in some December weather, and it seemed worthwhile to take a flutter on a dip.
https://www.dsv.com/en-nl/about-dsv/press/news/nl/2022/09/2022-golden-week-china
July 2022 was 70% of July 2021. If that roughly continues we will just about be just around 40m.
Probably fewer than last December, but not 30% lower, that feels a bit too extreme. The world is different to 12 months ago, but is it 30% different?
Jul 22 = 34m. 30% drop to last year.
https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-09-01/chengdu-fears-shanghai-repeat-as-cities-fall-to-xi-s-covid-zero

https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/chinas-big-cities-from-dalian-to-shenzhen-ramp-up-covid-curbs/ar-AA11gg4OIf they haven't ended covid zero now, hard to see them doing it during winter, when another wave becomes more likely
Tightening of the range with a bit more conviction towards the 40-80 ranges. 100m+ still not impossible, although covid cases are flaring up around Beijing so that is one to watch.
I think the crowd forecast has been influenced by anchoring effects.
Could be anything, if they have another lockdown like April they could drop below 20m, but otherwise I would assume it will be higher than last winter

Looking at the past figures we can clearly see the impact of Covid restrictions. While they are starting to make their Covid passports more interconnected so more travel can happen, the zero Covid policy looks like it will keep going at the very least until autumn. So December is quite hard to predict as things might start changing by then.
